TADA Final Project: Lobbying Influence on Congressmembers’ Tweets about Guns and the Environment

Jean Pierre Salendres, Sarah Kennedy, and Michelangelo Freyrie

12/21/2020

1 Idea and Research Question

We set out to understand the impact of lobbying on Congressional communication on Twitter.

What can lobbying funds tell us about Congress members public rhetoric about key issues?

We will look specifically at two fields: the environment and gun control.

Hypothesis: We expect that Congresspeople who receive more funds from lobbyists on bills they have sponsored related to gun control or the environemnt will tweet more often about these respective issues. Moreover, controlling for party, higher lobbying levels will also lead to more negatively/positively charged speech on these issues.

We chose to work with data from the House of Representatives because they are typically more closely aligned with local interests and are more accountable to them (as they represent a smaller group of citizens) than Senators.

1.1.8 Wrangling Lobby Data

#downsize sponsored bills
sponsored_bills <- read_delim("sponsored_bills.csv",";", escape_double = FALSE, trim_ws = TRUE)
new1 <- subset.data.frame(sponsored_bills, sponsored_bills$report_year > "2014")
new_sponsored_bills <- na.omit(new1, Var = c("congress_id_handles.Tweetcongress"))
#write.csv(new_sponsored_bills,"new_sponsored_bills", row.names = FALSE)

#downsize lobbying contributions file
dataset_report_level <- read_csv("dataset___report_level.csv")
money1 <- subset.data.frame(dataset_report_level, dataset_report_level$report_year > "2014") 
money2 <- subset.data.frame(money1, money1$amount != "$0.00")
#write.csv(money2,"new_dataset_report_level", row.names = FALSE)

#merge amount with congressmen dataset 
TADA_data <- merge(x = money2, y = new_sponsored_bills, by = "client_uuid", all = FALSE)
#write.csv(TADA_data,"TADA_data", row.names = FALSE)

#downsize issue code lobby data to relevant ones for and environment
dataset_issue_level <- read_csv("dataset___issue_level.csv")
issues_env1 <- subset.data.frame(dataset_issue_level, dataset_issue_level$issue_code == list("ENV", "TRA","FUE","ENG", "NAT", "CHM")) 
issues_env <- subset.data.frame(issues_env1, issues_env1$gov_entity == '{"HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES",SENATE}')

#downsize issue code lobby data to relevant ones for and environment
issues_gun1 <- subset.data.frame(dataset_issue_level, dataset_issue_level$issue_code == "FIR") 
issues_gun <- subset.data.frame(issues_gun1, issues_gun1$gov_entity == '{"HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES",SENATE}')

#DATA ENV : merge with issue codes, this will be the FINAL dataset on the lobby side we will need. 
TADA_env_data <- merge(x = TADA_data, y = issues_env, by = "report_uuid", all = FALSE)
#write.csv(TADA_env_data,"TADA_env_2015-2020", row.names = FALSE)

#DATA GUN : merge with issue codes, this will be the FINAL dataset on the lobby side we will need. 
TADA_gun_data <- merge(x = TADA_data, y = issues_gun, by = "report_uuid", all = FALSE)
#write.csv(TADA_gun_data,"TADA_gun_2015-2020", row.names = FALSE)

1.1.9 Calculations

#add up total lobby for each congressmen dataset
TADA_gun_data$amount <- as.factor(as.character(TADA_gun_data$amount)) 
TADA_gun_data$amount <- as.numeric(as.factor(TADA_gun_data$amount)) 


TADA_env_data$amount <- as.factor(as.character(TADA_env_data$amount)) 
TADA_env_data$amount <- as.numeric(as.factor(TADA_env_data$amount)) 

#sum for each congressman lobby money for env
money_env_totals <- TADA_env_data %>%
  group_by(congress_id_handles.TweetCongress, issue_code) %>% 
  transmute(Total=sum(amount))

money_env_peryear <- TADA_env_data %>%
  group_by(congress_id_handles.TweetCongress, issue_code, report_year.x) %>% 
  transmute(Total=sum(amount))

#sum for each congressman lobby money for guns
money_gun_totals <- TADA_gun_data %>%
  group_by(congress_id_handles.TweetCongress, issue_code) %>% 
  transmute(Total=sum(amount))

money_gun_peryear <- TADA_gun_data %>%
  group_by(congress_id_handles.TweetCongress, issue_code, report_year.x) %>% 
  transmute(Total=sum(amount))

1.2 ANALYSIS

1.2.1 LOBBYING

Lobby Data Acquisition: Using data acquired from LobbyView.org, a group dedicated to “advancing data science research in interest group politics,” we were able to determine the amount of money received by congresspeople in 2019 and 2020 per bill that they sponsored. All examined bills were related to gun issues.
To explore the influence of lobbying contributions on Twitter speech, we needed lobby monetary contribution data for 1) environment and gun legislation and for 2) individual members of Congress. LobbyView is an open-source website with lobby data for the United States. Their data spans the entire government. We focused on lobbying made to members of the House of Representatives (to match our Twitter data). The original data is sprad over 5 spreadsheets and we focused on gathering the relevant area and segmenting it in order to downsize files and have the specific data necessary for our study.

The Lobby data is linked to bills sponsored in the House of Representatives and we link this money to Congressmen sponsors of the bill. This means that the monetary lobby contriution is not direct to the congress member but encompasses a lobby effort for the sponsored bill in question. This link is sufficient since our hypothesis points to these lobbying contributions as influencers of debate on the house floor (sponsored bills) and Congress member’s public rhetoric (Tweets).

Our large lobby dataset contains dozens of variables that help us match data to twitter handles, Congressmen names, lobby firms, house bills, dates, etc. For simplicity of our treatment study (effect of lobbying), we segmented this data into two sub-datasets. Both our ‘gun’ (df_money_gun_peryear) and ‘environment’ (df_money_env_peryear) lobbying sub-datasets contain the folowing variables:

  • report_year: year of lobby contributions
  • congressman_twitter_handle: Congressman handle for lobby recipient
  • amount(treatment variable): the percentage of voters from the total number of eligible registered voters for a given county
  • issue_code: the presence of centralized vote center

1.2.2 LOBBYING VISUALIZATION

From the two graphs below, we can see the variation of lobby contributions for sponsors of gun-related bills and sponsors of environemntal-related bills. The gun-related lobbying for individual Congress members goes up to 25,000 dollars per year, while the environmental-related lobbying for individual Caongress members goes past a million dollars.

It is important to note thet in the environemntal-related lobbying chart below we have included various lobby areas that are linked in some way to the general idea of environment. We expect that most of these areas will have a negative speech effect, or abstinence of pro-environemnt speech, on Congressmen i.e. Chemicals, Fuels, Transport). Environment is the only variable that we expect to have a positive effect on speech pro-environment. Lastly, we expect Energy to be mixed and produce more conversation on the environment but on both negative and positive directions, due to the variance of energy groups across energy sources (some more environmentally-friendly than others).

1.2.3 TWEETS

Twitter Data Acquisition: Using the Twitter API, we pulled 75,000 (25k/group member) Tweets from all 435 Members of the House of Representatives’ official accounts. We took a list of Congressmen from the 115th Congress (Jan 2017- Jan 2019). The tweets span from 205 to 2020, as some Congressmen have been in Congress pre-115th Congress and post 115th Congress. We keep these dates in mind throughout the analysis and focus on the 115th Congress (full list of members) but consider pre and post 115th congress data to see Congress members longer speech trends.

We use this data as evidence of the political communication surrounding important issues for the Congress member and his audience, including on gun control and environmental legislation. We assume that there is an incentive for congress members to use Twitter communication to disseminated their views and political interests.

Below are a few visualizations of the twitter data we have for all Congress members:

Here we see the frquency of words most used in tweets. The terms are quite general and political in nature (america, support, pass, vote, legislation, great, trump, right, care). But these are too broad for our interests.

1.2.4 ANALYSIS

As can be seen in the code sections, we created a dictionary for environment-debate terms and one for gun-debate related terms. These dictionaries helped us analyse the twitter data from all congressmen and create counts for hits of the dictionary on the individuals’ tweets.

As with all dictionary creation, more research and time should be devoted to perfect the dictionary (if that is ever possible) so we may get better coverage and precision.

These dictionaries allowed us to create the variation among congressmen that we needed in order to evaluate our hypothesis of whether lobby money affects the degree to which a congress member talks about these issues.

As indicated in the lobby code, the lobby data has been curated to create lobby contribution totals

1.2.5 THE MODEL

PART I: DEPENDENT VARIABLE (DV)

Congressmembers Twitter data analyzed through the prism of environmental and gun dictionaries will form the basis of our dependent variable (counts of related vocabulary use)

PART II: INDEPENDENT VARIABLES + CONTROLS

The lobby data that has been segmented by total lobby contributions for each congress members in 1) gun-related areas and 2)environmental related areas. The latter includes contributions by lobbies in areas of transport, fuels, natural resources, energy, that we expect to have negative coefficients and to reduce environmental speech of the congress member. We expect environment to be the only variable with a positive coefficient. Contributions are much lower in this area and therefore we are mainly looking at the “anti-environment” lobby areas described. The assumption we have is that these areas will push congress members to focus less on environment since the lobby areas rely on fossil fuels, natural resources, or other polluting susbtances.

We will run this totals as variation to see effect on IV. Some controls added are the year and lobby issue sub-code.

We can see that for each dollar received from the gun lobby decreases congress members gun speech by -0.023 words, a statistically significant result with 99% confidence level. This is small yet considerable since it is attached to total dollar amount which goes up to 25,000 dollars in our dataset for gun lobbying contributions.

Therefore, someone who receives 25,000 USD will use 575 less gun related words or phrases from our dictionary. Notice that the constant and the year coefficient balance each other out (8,519 (constant) + year*(-4.189)) = 8,519 - (8440 to 8461) depending on year 2ß15-2020. Therefore from 59 to 79 dictionary words vary per year and the rest is an effect of lobby controbution coefficient.

The observations are too small and therefore we need to raise the quality of data to have more statistical power.

For the environemntal part, we see the coefficients for each lobby area. We expected negative coefficients for all exceot for Environment. In the results, we see that we have a few robust results, for example for transport and natural resources lobby, having a strong negatuve impact on pro-environmental langauge use in Tweets from Congressmembers.

Our observations are much higher here but our main coefficient however, is not statistically significant although it is in the right (negative) direction. The coeff is small but since donations go all the way to 1.2 million dollars for some congress members in total, that coefficient could be significant in terms of word usage in twets. However, it is not statistically significant so further analysis needs to be done.

Specifically, we mixed a few areas of lobbying and this could have counteracted the effects of areas that may be relevant.

However we encountered several problems that should be further looked into to make the analysis more robust:

I. In the course of our dictionary creation, the gun-related and environmental-related dictionaries decreased our congress member count significantly. This seems to be a code bug issue that we could not overcome too well, since for both lists the congress members were small (but complete) There is no reason to believe dozens of other members should not have come up, since they also had words related to gun or environment in their tweets.

  1. When merging with the lobby data, we went flost some additional congress members, after dropping those that did not have contributions. These numbers should be brougth up if we fix the issue described in Part I.

  2. The model would benefit from additional controls for age of congress member, geographic region, and others that can help us analyse speech use and control for variation due tot hese ommitted variables.
